<hr>
<h3>Playing with metaphors</h3>
<p>
  So much of DNS is about routing and destinations. This project seemed like a great place to play with metaphors
  so DNS newbies could grasp concepts more quickly.
</p>
<div class="figure-container smaller">
  <figure>
    <%= render "shared/video_figure", video_asset_path_name: "dnsdigest-mx.webm" %>
    <figcaption>
      <span><strong>SMTP &rarr; IMAP:</strong> Rather than seeing a 
      typical list of <span class="dns-label">MX</span> records, I show how they group together
      by priority and what services these emails point to in the design of airline tickets.
      </span>
    </figcaption>
  </figure>
</div>
<div class="figure-container smaller">
  <figure>
    <%= render "shared/video_figure", video_asset_path_name: "dnsdigest-mappings.webm" %>
    <figcaption>
      <span>
        <strong>DNS express:</strong> 
        In a more subtle nudge, with <span class="dns-label">A</span>, <span class="dns-label">AAAA</span> , 
        and <span class="dns-label">CNAME</span> records,
        I display how they map to IP addresses in a format similar to a destination board you would 
        see at a train station. Users can also add notes to records to help them remember what they mean.
      </span>
    </figcaption>
  </figure>
</div>
<hr>
<h3>Explaining email deliverability</h3>
<p>
  For <span class="dns-label">SPF</span> and <span class="dns-label">DMARC</span> records, I show 
  how to interpret their <span class="dns-label">TXT</span> values. I also built an SPF lookup crawler
  that counts unique lookups to determine if they are over the recommended 10 maximum lookup limit.
</p>
